Or better yet for more control:

```rust
#[wasm_bindgen]
fn send_message(name: String) -> Result<(), String> {
    // name is now owned by the function in Rust
    let output = format!("Hello, {}!", name);
    Ok(())
}
```
The key takeaway from all this: when you want to pass a `&str` or `&T` between Rust and WASM, you must ensure you're not consuming the value. If JS modifies it (which they often do), you need a way for Rust to communicate back that change occurred. That's why returning a `Result<T>` with an owned string is usually safer than passing by reference unless you know exactly what JS will do next.
